[Event "Short & Sweet: Anti-Sicilians"]
[Site "S&S: Anti-Sicilians"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. b3"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Anti-Sicilians"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-anti-sicilians-/course/31820, variation/5898072"]

1. e4 c5 2. b3 {[%cal Bc1b2,Gb2h8,Bf2f4] The fianchetto of the dark-squared 
bishop does not pretend to seek advantage, but White gets a playable position 
with a lot of pieces on the board. If White wants to play b3 it makes sense to 
do it immediately, as opposed to 2. Nf3 d6 3. b3 as with the knight on f3 there 
are no ideas based on f2-f4.} Nc6 {[%cal Bd7d6,Be7e6] Black will develop in 
Scheveningen style, with his pieces in the centre and ready to react to whatever 
White tries.} 3. Bb2 d6 {A multi-purpose move: if allowed Black would want to 
close the long diagonal by ...e5 and then develop by ...g6, ...Bg7, ...Nge7, 
...O-O.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5e8]} Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] Of course, Black wants to take 
on c6 with a bishop.} 5. f4 {[%cal Gf4e5] Preventing ...e5.} Nf6 {[%cal 
Gb2g7,Be7e6,Bf8e7,Be8g8] Since ...e5 has been prevented, Black continues in 
Scheveningen style, with ...e6 and ...Be7 to come next.} 6. Qe2 {[%cal 
Rb2f6,Re7f6] Taking on f6 would be great for Black, who would take with the 
e-pawn and remain with an unopposed dark-squared bishop that will be developed 
on g7 after ...g6 and later opened up by ...f5.} e6 7. Nf3 Be7 {[%cal 
Ba7a6,Bb7b5][%csl Ge8] Black finished his development and the only thing that 
remains is the position of the king. But Black needn't hurry with this decision, 
as he has useful moves at his disposal, like ...a6 and possibly a queenside 
expansion by ...b5.} 8. O-O O-O {[%csl Gg8] With both kings on the kingside 
Black is perfectly safe.} 9. d3 a6 {[%cal Ga6b5][%csl Rb5] Black wins the bishop 
pair and even though the position is rather closed this is good for his 
long-term prospects.} 10. Bxc6 Bxc6 {[%cal Bb7b5] Black has a very pleasant 
position. He expands on the queenside in typical Sicilian fashion.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Anti-Sicilians"]
[Site "S&S: Anti-Sicilians"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Ne2"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Anti-Sicilians"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-anti-sicilians-/course/31820, variation/5898077"]

1. e4 c5 2. Ne2 {[%cal Bc2c4,Bd2d4] Similar to 2. c4 this move aims for a 
Maroczy structure after c4 and d4. Now unless Black plays the Accelerated 
Fianchetto and allows the Maroczy, in which case he can play 2... d6, allowing 
3. c4 and then d4, or he plays the Taimanov and he plays 2... e6 allowing 3. c4 
and then d4, he has only one acceptable move here and that one is} Nf6 $1 {[%cal 
Gf6e4] Attacking the e4-pawn and forcing White's next move, thus preventing c4.} 
3. Nbc3 {[%cal Gc3e4]} d5 {[%cal Gd5e4]} ({The move} 3... d6 {would lead to a 
transposition to a fianchetto line of another open Sicilian after} 4. g3 {and 
then d4.}) ({On the other hand, the move} 3... Nc6 {is perfectly acceptable for 
Sveshnikov players.}) 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Nxd5 Qxd5 6. d4 {[%cal Gd4c5]} ({The 
alternative is} 6. Nc3 {when after} 6... Qe5 {Black is comfortably equal. He 
will finish development by ...e6 and ...Be7 (or ...g6 and ...Bg7) and will play 
on the d-file.}) e5 {[%cal Gc5d4,Ge5d4,Gd5d1]} 7. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5]} ({Taking on 
e5 is harmless, after} 7. dxe5 Qxe5 8. c3 Be7 {Black will castle with a good 
position.}) Qxd4 8. Be3 {[%cal Ge3d4] White tries to prove that his lead in 
development and the active pieces compensate for the pawn.} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4d1] 
This disruptive move forces further exchanges.} 9. Bxd4 Bxd1 10. Bxe5 Bxc2 11. 
Kd2 Bf5 {[%csl Rd2] It is not very likely that White will return the pawn, so he 
must bank on his activity. This puts more pressure on White to play precise 
moves because if he fails to do so he will simply be a pawn down for nothing. 
After} 12. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e8][%csl Re8]} Kd7 13. Kc1 Nc6 {Black is fine as White 
doesn't have obvious compensation.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Anti-Sicilians"]
[Site "S&S: Anti-Sicilians"]
