[Round "?"]
[White "The Morra Gambit"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Anti-Sicilians"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-anti-sicilians-/course/31820, variation/5898080"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3 {The notorious Morra (or Smith-Morra) Gambit. The 
gambit is quite an exciting and very aggressive choice against the Sicilian and 
can be very dangerous. If accepted, White's play is automatic and easy, which is 
very important in a practical game.} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4][%csl Gd4] A very rare line 
against the Morra whose idea is to turn the tables on the gambiteer. After this 
move White has two options, neither of which is in line with the aggressive 
intentions of the gambit.} 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d4,Gf3e5]} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gc6e5]} 
5. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4f7] With this move White chooses to accept a sacrifice and 
subject himself to a long-term attack.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] Now the game resembles 
the Two Knights Defence.} 6. Ng5 {[%cal Gg5f7,Gc4f7][%csl Rf7]} d5 {[%cal 
Rc4f7,Gd5c4,Gd5e4] The only way to defend f7.} 7. exd5 Na5 {[%cal Ga5c4] The 
moves are the same as in the Two Knights.} 8. Bb5+ Bd7 {[%cal Gd7b5]} 9. Qe2 
{[%cal Ge2b5,Ge2e5][%csl Re5]} Bd6 {[%cal Gd6e5,Be8g8][%csl Ra5] Defending the 
pawn on e5 and preparing castling. Black sacrifices the knight on a5, which 
doesn't have a square to go to, in order to finish his development and push back 
White's pieces.} 10. b4 {[%cal Gb4a5][%csl Ra5]} h6 {[%cal Gh6g5] First the 
knight is pushed back.} 11. Nf3 O-O {[%csl Gd7,Gd6,Gf6,Gg8,Ra5] Black is fully 
developed, but the price to pay was the knight on a5. Still, after} 12. bxa5 d3 
$1 {[%cal Ge5e4,Ge4f3,Ge4d3][%csl Rd3] Is a nice move to make, as White cannot 
take on d3 in view of the fork after ...e4.} 13. Qb2 e4 {[%cal Ge4f3][%csl 
Ge4,Gd3] Defending the advanced pawn on d3 and gaining more time to develop the 
initiative. Black has fantastic compensation in this position.} *

