[White "The Alapin Variation"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Anti-Sicilians"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-anti-sicilians-/course/31820, variation/5898084"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 {[%cal Gc3d4,Bd2d4] The Alapin Variation is a very popular option 
against the Sicilian because it is relatively easy to play with White.} d5 {The 
central push is one of the main lines and gives Black free play.} 3. exd5 Qxd5 
4. d4 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4,Bd4c5,Be8c8] Black develops the queenside first.} 5. Nf3 
{[%cal Gf3d4]} Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1][%csl Rd4] Black plays for quick queenside 
development.} 6. Be2 {[%csl Rd4] With this move White goes for the IQP 
position.} cxd4 {Immediately creating the IQP.} 7. cxd4 {[%csl Rd4]} e6 {[%cal 
Bg8f6,Bf8e7,Be8g8] Black will now develop the kingside and will obtain a 
comfortable position with play against the IQP.} 8. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5][%csl Gd5] 
White attacks the exposed queen.} Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1][%csl Rd5,Re1]} ({Black 
develops with tempo as} 8... Qa5 {allows} 9. d5) 9. O-O Qa5 {[%cal Ga5c3][%csl 
Rc3] The queen moves to a safe square and puts pressure on the knight on c3.} 
10. h3 {[%cal Gh3g4] This forces the exchange of the bishop.} Bxf3 {[%cal 
Rf3d4][%csl Rd4] Black must not lose time. He takes on f3 in order to gain tempo 
to develop the knight from g8.} 11. Bxf3 Nge7 {[%cal Be8g8,Be7f5,Gf5d4][%csl 
Rd4] This is the position Black has been aiming for. He has comfortable 
development and after castling he will start the play against the IQP. The 
knight is developed on e7 rather than on f6 because from e7 it can go to f5 to 
increase the pressure on the d4-pawn.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Anti-Sicilians"]
[Site "S&S: Anti-Sicilians"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Nc3, 3. Nf3 Variation #1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Anti-Sicilians"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-anti-sicilians-/course/31820, variation/5898088"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {This is the trickiest move to meet only for the Najdorf player. 
The reason lies in the fact that White doesn't want to play a Najdorf, but at 
the same time he keeps the option to transpose to an open Sicilian by d2-d4 at a 
certain point.} Nc6 {[%cal Rd7d6,Gd7d5,Ge7e6] All these considerations led me to 
my suggestion of the move 2... Nc6. With this move and his subsequent play Black 
will prevent any transposition to an open Sicilian.} 3. Nf3 {[%cal Rd2d4,Gf3d4]} 
e5 {[%cal Ge5d4] Preventing d4 with a transposition to an open Sicilian.} 4. Bc4 
Be7 {[%cal Ge7g5,Rf3g5] It is important to keep the g5-square under control in 
order to prevent Ng5.} 5. d3 {[%cal Bf3d2,Bd2f1,Bf1e3,Be1g1,Bf2f4]} d6 ({Again, 
not} 5... Nf6 {as it allows} 6. Ng5 {.}) 6. Nd2 {[%cal Bd2f1,Bf1e3,Ge3f5,Ge3d5] 
This is the more positional approach. White wants to put the knight on the ideal 
e3-square, from where it will control d5 and f5.} Nf6 {Black continues his 
development.} 7. Nf1 {[%cal Bf1e3,Ge3d5,Ge3f5]} Nd7 $1 {[%cal Bd7b6,Gb6d5,Bf7f5] 
This maneuver was brought into the limelight by Magnus Carlsen. The idea is to 
continue the fight for the d5-square from b6, rather than f6, thus not blocking 
the path of the f-pawn, which will allow for a counterplay-seeking ...f5 later 
on.} 8. Ne3 {White continues with his plan.} Nb6 {[%cal Gb6d5,Be8g8,Bf7f5,Be7g5] 
Finishing the knight maneuver.} 9. O-O {If White jumps to d5 with either knight 
then after an exchange there and castling by both sides the position will 
transpose to the main line.} O-O 10. Ncd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Be6 {[%cal 
Ge6d5,Bc6a5,Ga5c4,Bf7f5,Be7g5] A natural move, finishing development and keeping 
control of the d5-square. Now Black has three main ideas: to play ...Na5 to 
attack the bishop on c4, to play ...f5 and start kingside activity (at the same 
time being careful about the undefended bishop on e6), or to play ...Bg5 and 
exchange the dark-squared bishops.} *

