1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {This is the trickiest move to meet only for the Najdorf player. 
The reason lies in the fact that White doesn't want to play a Najdorf, but at 
the same time he keeps the option to transpose to an open Sicilian by d2-d4 at a 
certain point.} Nc6 {[%cal Rd7d6,Gd7d5,Ge7e6]} 3. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d4,Rd2d4]} e5 
{[%cal Ge5d4] Preventing d4 with a transposition to an open Sicilian.} 4. Bc4 
{[%cal Gc4f7,Bf3g5,Gg5f7][%csl Rf7]} Be7 {[%cal Ge7g5,Rf3g5] It is important to 
keep the g5-square under control in order to prevent Ng5.} 5. d3 {[%cal 
Bf3d2,Bd2f1,Bf1e3,Bf2f4,Be1g1]} d6 ({Again, not} 5... Nf6 {as it allows} 6. Ng5) 
6. O-O {With this move White will attempt to push f4 quickly enough. This line 
requires more theoretical knowledge and some memorisation as the lines are 
rather long.} Nf6 {[%cal Be8g8] Finishing the development of the kingside.} 7. 
Ng5 {This liberates the path for the f-pawn.} O-O 8. f4 {[%cal Gf1f7]} Bg4 
{[%cal Gg4d1][%csl Rd1] An important move. It finishes development and wins a 
tempo by attacking the queen.} 9. Qe1 {[%cal Be1g3,Bf4f5]} exf4 {[%cal Rf4f5] 
Eliminating the threat of f5.} 10. Bxf4 Nd4 {[%cal Gd4c2][%csl Rc2,Gd4] 
Centralising the knight and attacking c2.} 11. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2c2]} h6 {[%cal 
Gh6g5]} 12. Nf3 Nxf3+ {Black now exchanges a pair of light pieces.} 13. gxf3 
{[%cal Gg1g8]} Be6 {[%cal Ge6c4][%csl Rc4] The bishop on c4 is strong so Black 
seeks to exchange it. Black has a very solid position and his main strategic 
idea is to push ...d5.} *

