[White "Closed Sicilian #1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Anti-Sicilians"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-anti-sicilians-/course/31820, variation/5898091"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {This is the trickiest move to meet only for the Najdorf player. 
The reason lies in the fact that White doesn't want to play a Najdorf, but at 
the same time he keeps the option to transpose to an open Sicilian by d2-d4 at a 
certain point.} Nc6 3. g3 {[%cal Bf1g2,Bf2f4,Bf2f5] The Closed Sicilian leads to 
relatively calm play, though Black must be a bit careful about a possible 
f5-push in the middlegame.} g6 {[%cal Bf8g7,Gg7a1][%csl Gd4,Ge5] The kingside 
fianchetto is the best reaction to the Closed Sicilian. The bishop from g7 
controls the central squares d4 and e5 and helps the queenside attack.} 4. Bg2 
Bg7 5. d3 d6 {[%cal Gd6c5] The most flexible move, defending c5 first. Now White 
two main options at his disposal.} 6. Be3 Rb8 {[%cal 
Bb7b5,Re7e6,Rg8e7,Gg8h6][%csl Gh6] Since with his last move White prepared the 
move Qd2, aiming to exchange the fianchettoed bishop on g7 in case Black plays 
...e6 and ...Nge7, Black first postpones this development of the kingside and 
starts his own typical queenside expansion.} 7. Qd2 b5 8. f4 {[%cal Bf4f5]} b4 
{[%cal Gg7b2][%csl Rb2] Expanding on the queenside and forcing the knight to go 
to d1 to defend the b2-pawn.} 9. Nd1 {[%cal Gd1b2]} e6 {[%cal Bg8e7,Rd2h6][%csl 
Rf4] Black achieved the maximum on the queenside for the time being so now he 
finishes the development of the kingside. With the pawn on f4 there is no threat 
to exchange the dark-squared bishops.} 10. Nf3 {[%cal Bd3d4,Gf3d4] The threat is 
to play d4, so Black prevents it by putting his knight on d4.} Nd4 {[%csl Gd4]} 
11. O-O Ne7 {[%cal Be8g8] Black almost finished development, all remains is to 
castle and then continue with his queenside play.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Anti-Sicilians"]
[Site "S&S: Anti-Sicilians"]
