[Round "?"]
[White "Closed Sicilian #2"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: Anti-Sicilians"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-anti-sicilians-/course/31820, variation/5898090"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {This is the trickiest move to meet only for the Najdorf player. 
The reason lies in the fact that White doesn't want to play a Najdorf, but at 
the same time he keeps the option to transpose to an open Sicilian by d2-d4 at a 
certain point.} Nc6 3. g3 {[%cal Bf1g2,Bf2f4,Bf4f5] The Closed Sicilian leads to 
relatively calm play, though Black must be a bit careful about a possible 
f5-push in the middlegame.} g6 {[%cal Bf8g7,Gg7a1][%csl Gd4,Ge5] The kingside 
fianchetto is the best reaction to the Closed Sicilian. The bishop from g7 
controls the central squares d4 and e5 and helps the queenside attack.} 4. Bg2 
Bg7 5. d3 d6 {[%cal Gd6c5] The most flexible move, defending c5 first. Now White 
two main options at his disposal.} 6. f4 {[%cal Bf4f5] This is the other main 
move in this position.} e6 {[%cal Bg8e7,Ge7f5,Ge6f5] Black develops in the 
flexible manner - the knight from e7 will control the f5-square.} 7. Nf3 Nge7 8. 
O-O O-O 9. Be3 {[%cal Bd3d4,Ge3d4] This is an important moment. With his last 
move White is threatening to push d4, so Black must stop this. In the Closed 
Sicilian Black needs to know what he should do on the kingside and the 
queenside. These strategic themes are covered in the model games 
Turovsky-Dvoretsky and Bronstein-Dvoretsky.} Nd4 $1 {[%cal Rd3d4][%csl Gd4] The 
only way to stop d4. Note that the knight should jump to d4 only when d4 is 
threatened.} 10. e5 {[%cal Rg7d4,Ge5d6] This is the most concrete attempt. The 
others are more in spirit of the Closed Sicilian, but do not pose real problems. 
For example 10. Qd2 can be met by 10... Rb8 and then ... b5-b4.} Bd7 {[%cal 
Bd7c6,Gc6g2][%csl Re4] The idea is to come with the bishop on c6, once the long 
diagonal has been opened.} 11. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4d6][%csl Rd6] Targeting d6.} Nef5 
{[%cal Gf5d6,Gf5d4,Gf5e3] Attacking the bishop and keeping control over d6.} 12. 
Bf2 Nxf3+ {[%cal Bf5d4] Since both knights want to be on d4 this makes the 
knight on f5 superfluous (this concept is from Dvoretsky's books!) so the 
solution is to exchange the knight already on the desired square so that the 
other one can land there. Hence the logic of Black's move.} 13. Qxf3 Bc6 {[%cal 
Gc6f3] The square where the bishop was headed to. The middlegame is complex, but 
Black has excellent development and pressure against White's centre.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: Anti-Sicilians"]
[Site "S&S: Anti-Sicilians"]
