[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-anti-sicilians-/course/31820, variation/5898089"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {This is the trickiest move to meet only for the Najdorf player. 
The reason lies in the fact that White doesn't want to play a Najdorf, but at 
the same time he keeps the option to transpose to an open Sicilian by d2-d4 at a 
certain point.} Nc6 3. Bb5 {[%cal Bb5c6,Rf3d4][%csl Gd4] This is similar to the 
Rossolimo, having the same idea to take on c6 and double Black's c-pawns. 
However, unlike the Rossolimo, here the d4-square isn't controlled by the 
knight, so Black uses that fact to remove the knight from c6 at the same time 
attacking the bishop on b5.} Nd4 {[%cal Gd4b5] It is better not to allow White 
to take on c6.} 4. Bc4 {This is the most commonly played move, but while the 
alternatives are equally possible they tend to transpose to the main line.} e6 
{[%cal Ba7a6,Bb7b5,Bd7d5,Rc4f7] Blunting the bishop. Black will now aim to 
either push ...d5 or ...a6 and ...b5, going after the bishop.} 5. Nf3 {[%cal 
Gf3d4]} Nf6 {Continuing development.} 6. O-O ({Not fearing} 6. e5 {in view of 6} 
... d5) a6 {[%cal Bb7b5] This move is needed to cover b5 against a possible 
check and also as means to prepare ...b5.} 7. d3 b5 {[%cal Gb5c4,Bd4b3] Forcing 
the exchange of the knight on d4 for the light-squared bishop, thus winning the 
bishop pair.} 8. Bb3 Nxb3 {Black obtains the bishop pair and keeps a very solid 
position.} 9. axb3 Bb7 {[%cal Ra1a8,Gb7a8,Gb7e4] The bishop will be excellent on 
the long diagonal. At the same time this move defends the b5-pawn against Nxb5 
by defending the rook on a8.} *

