1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {This is the trickiest move to meet only for the Najdorf player. 
The reason lies in the fact that White doesn't want to play a Najdorf, but at 
the same time he keeps the option to transpose to an open Sicilian by d2-d4 at a 
certain point.} Nc6 3. f4 {The starting point of the Grand Prix Attack, but this 
doesn't work so well for White with the pawn still on d7.} g6 {[%cal 
Bf8g7,Gg7d4,Rd2d4][%csl Gd4] The kingside fianchetto is the best plan against 
the Grand Prix Attack.} 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bc4 {Is less effective because after} e6 
{[%cal Rc4f7,Bg8e7,Bd7d5][%csl Rc4] A logical move that blunts the bishop, Black 
is ready for ...Nge7 and ...d5.} 6. O-O ({The alternative is the aggressive} 6. 
f5 {but after} 6... Nge7 7. fxe6 dxe6 {Black's kingside is ultra-solid, with the 
bishop on c4 being particularly useless.}) Nge7 {[%cal Be8g8,Bd7d5,Ge7d5]} 7. d3 
({Starting with} 7. Qe1 {leads to a transposition after} 7... O-O 8. d3 d5) O-O 
8. Qe1 {[%cal Be1h4]} d5 {[%cal Gd5c4,Gd5e4] Black expands in the centre.} 9. 
Bb3 Na5 {[%cal Ga5b3,Bb7b6,Bc8b7][%csl Rb3] Black will obtain the bishop pair 
and develop by ...b6 and ...Bb7. It is important that White has no attack 
whatsoever.} *

