1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {This is the trickiest move to meet only for the Najdorf player. 
The reason lies in the fact that White doesn't want to play a Najdorf, but at 
the same time he keeps the option to transpose to an open Sicilian by d2-d4 at a 
certain point.} Nc6 3. f4 {The starting point of the Grand Prix Attack, but this 
doesn't work so well for White with the pawn still on d7.} g6 {[%cal 
Bf8g7,Gg7d4,Rd3d4,Rd2d4][%csl Gd4] The kingside fianchetto is the best plan 
against the Grand Prix Attack.} 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5 {[%cal Bb5c6]} Nd4 {[%cal 
Bd4b5,Rb5c6][%csl Gd4] Of course, Black avoids the possible doubling of the 
c-pawns.} 6. O-O {[%cal Bd2d3,Bd1e1,Be1h4,Bf4f5] The alternatives are worse, so 
White speeds up his development.} Nxb5 {Taking this bishop always feels good.} 
7. Nxb5 d5 {[%cal Ge4d5] Striking in the centre and changing the structure. Now 
White doesn't have the easy play typical for the Grand Prix Attack with d3, 
Qe1-h4, f5 etc.} 8. e5 {The only way to try for something.} a6 {[%cal Ga6b5] 
Chasing away the knight. Black will now play for a better structure.} 9. Nc3 Bg4 
{[%cal Be7e6,Bg8e7,Bg4f3][%csl Gd5] Black's plan is to exchange the 
light-squared bishop and play ...e6, thus making sure he has the better bishop 
(not restricted by his own pawns).} 10. d4 cxd4 11. Qxd4 Bxf3 {Before the knight 
could move Black is eliminating it.} 12. Rxf3 e6 {[%cal 
Ba8c8,Bg8e7,Bg7f8,Gf8a3,Gc8c1,Ge7c6,Ge7f5][%csl Gg7,Rc1,Gc6,Gf5] This is the 
structure Black is aiming for - it is the same structure that can arise from the 
French or the Sicilian after Black had pushed ...d5 and White had played e5. 
Here Black has the better bishop - this will become apparent once it is 
transferred via f8 and his knight also has good prospects going to either f5 or 
c6. His structure is also better, as once he finishes development he can try to 
use the c-file to his advantage.} *

