1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bc4 {[%cal Bc2c3,Bd2d3,Bd2d4,Bb1d2,Bd2f1,Bf1g3] This aims 
to obtain a Spanish-like position after c3, d3 followed by the typical maneuver 
Nbd2-f1-g3. White will also try to push d4 and obtain a full centre if 
possible.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] By attacking the e4-pawn Black forces White to 
defend it by d3, thus preventing possible ideas with quick c3 and d4.} 4. d3 
{[%cal Gd3e4]} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4]} 5. c3 {[%cal Gc3d4,Bd3d4] White also follows 
his plan of play as in the Spanish.} g6 {[%cal Bf8g7,Gg7a1][%csl Gd4] The 
fianchetto will enable the bishop to exert pressure in the centre.} 6. O-O Bg7 
7. Bb3 {[%cal Bf1e1,Bd3d4]} O-O 8. Re1 {White prepares for the Nbd2-f1-g3 
maneuver.} b5 {[%cal Gg7c3,Bb5b4,Gb4c3][%csl Rc3] Threatening ...b4. Black's 
play is similar to the Closed Sicilian, as he expands on the queenside and 
attempts to create weaknesses there.} 9. a3 {[%cal Ga3b4] White prevents ...b4 
as against the other moves Black would play it. Note that White cannot advance 
in the centre by 9 d4 because after 9... cd 10 cd Bg4 Black already is very 
active and threatens to take on f3, thus ruining White's structure.} a5 {[%cal 
Ra1a8,Ba5a4,Ga5b4,Ga4b3] Since ...b4 isn't possible in view of the pin on the 
a-file after axb4, Black now advances with the a-pawn to a4 in order to fix the 
light-squared weaknesses (in particular the b3-square) left by White's last 
move.} 10. h3 {[%cal Gh3g4,Rc8g4]} Nd7 {[%cal 
Bd7b6,Ba5a4,Bc6a5,Ga5c4,Gb6c4,Rd3c4,Rd3d4,Gg7d4] A fine maneuver. The knight is 
aiming for b6, anticipating a possible d4, which would weaken the c4-square. The 
control over c4 can further be increased after ...a4 and ...Na5.} 11. Be3 {White 
refrains from playing d4.} a4 {Black continues with his plan to get a grip on 
the light squares on the queenside.} 12. Bc2 Nb6 {[%cal Gb6c4,Gb6d5] The knight 
arrived at its destination and now controls the c4-square. Black has a very 
comfortable position.} *

