1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. c3 {[%cal Gc3d4,Bd2d4] Apart from the Rossolimo, White has 
many other options on his 3rd move. The most theoretically important is the move 
3. c3. In this variation Black has two general plans at his disposal: the 
fianchetto of the dark-squared bishop and the ...Bg4 pin followed by ...e6.} Nf6 
{[%cal Bc8g4,Be7e6,Bg7g6,Rd2d4]} 4. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3e4,Bd3c2,Bd2d4,Rh2h3] White 
wants to put the bishop on c2 and push d4, this time trying to make do without 
the h3 move.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4] Black develops normally to control the centre.} 
5. Bc2 {[%cal Bd2d4]} Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1,Rh2h3,Rf3d4][%csl Gd4] Black uses the 
fact that White omitted h3 and pins the knight, thus indirectly fighting against 
d4.} 6. d3 {[%cal Rd2d4]} ({Since pushing} 6. d4 {brings nothing to White after} 
6... cxd4 7. cxd4 e6 {followed by ...d5, White resorts to slower play.}) e6 
{[%cal Rc8e6,Bd6d5,Ge6d5,Bf8e7] The bishop from c8 is out and Black can now 
develop the dark-squared bishop on e7. Additionally, the move ...e6 helps the 
central thrust ...d5.} 7. Nbd2 Be7 8. h3 Bh5 9. Nf1 {[%cal Bf1g3] White is 
regrouping but this is slow and allows Black to strike in the centre first.} d5 
{[%cal Gd5e4] This is the point of Black's opening play - he controls the centre 
well and strikes first.} 10. Qe2 c4 $1 {[%cal Gc4d3,Gd5e4][%csl Re4,Rd3] This is 
an important move to remember. Black destroys White's central structure.} *

