1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. c3 {[%cal Gc3d4,Bd2d4] Apart from the Rossolimo, White has 
many other options on his 3rd move. The most theoretically important is the move 
3. c3. In this variation Black has two general plans at his disposal: the 
fianchetto of the dark-squared bishop and the ...Bg4 pin followed by ...e6.} Nf6 
{[%cal Be7e6,Bg7g6,Bc8g4,Bf8g7,Rd2d4]} 4. h3 {[%cal Gh3g4,Rc8g4] This move 
prevents the pinning ...Bg4.} g6 {[%cal Bf8g7,Re7e6] The fianchetto is the only 
way for Black to develop the dark squared bishop without closing the bishop on 
c8 by playing ...e6.} 5. Bd3 {[%cal Bd2d4,Bd3c2,Be1g1] White now wants to play 
Bc2, O-O and d4.} Bg7 6. Bc2 e5 $1 {[%cal Gc5d4,Ge5d4,Rd2d4] An important move, 
the only way to continue the fight for the d4-square.} 7. O-O O-O 8. d3 {[%cal 
Bf7f5,Gg7d4][%csl Gg7]} ({The move} 8. d4 {while possible, is not good for White 
because after} 8... exd4 9. cxd4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nc6 {Black is better developed 
and is putting White's centre under pressure.}) Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4] Before 
deciding on his plan Black must first finish his development.} 9. Re1 {[%cal 
Bb1d2,Bd2f1,Bf1e3,Bf1g3] White prepares the typical Spanish maneuver Nbd2-f1-g3 
(e3).} b5 {[%cal Ba7a5,Ba5a4,Bb5b4,Rc6a5] Another aspect that is in Black's 
favour compared to the Spanish - he can start queenside expansion immediately, 
without sidelining the knight by ...Na5.} 10. Nbd2 a5 {[%cal 
Bb5b4,Ba5a4,Bd6d5,Bf7f5] Continuing the queenside expansion. Black has good 
development and can play on the whole board: push on the queenside, prepare 
...d5 or go for plans with ...f5.} *

