1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. c3 {[%cal Gc3d4,Bd2d4] Apart from the Rossolimo, White has 
many other options on his 3rd move. The most theoretically important is the move 
3. c3. In this variation Black has two general plans at his disposal: the 
fianchetto of the dark-squared bishop and the ...Bg4 pin followed by ...e6.} Nf6 
{[%cal Rd2d4,Bc8g4,Be7e6,Bg7g6,Bf8g7]} 4. Be2 {[%cal Rc8g4,Rg4e2,Be1g1] The most 
popular move in the position, but the others are just as likely to be played. 
White's general plan in the 3. c3 line is to obtain a full centre after castling 
and defending the e4-pawn or to get into a Spanish-like position after d3.} g6 
{[%cal Bf8g7]} 5. O-O Bg7 6. Bb5+ {[%cal Rb5e8,Bd2d4] This check gave some rise 
to the popularity of the line at the end of the 20th century. It allows White to 
defend the pawn on e4 without a loss of tempo and push d4.} Bd7 {Covering with 
the bishop like in the Moscow Variation in order to speed up the development.} 
7. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 {[%cal Rf1e2,Rf1b5] Black recaptures like in the Moscow 
Variation. In fact, he is a tempo up compared to the Moscow Variation since here 
White played Be2 before giving the check on b5.} 8. Re1 {[%cal Bd2d4,Ge1e4] 
White defends e4 and prepares d4.} O-O {Black finished development and his 
pieces are well-placed.} 9. d4 {[%cal Be4e5,Be4e6]} e6 {[%cal 
Re4e5,Re4e6,Ba8c8,Bc5d4,Gc8c1] A useful move, preventing the e5-e6 idea. Black's 
plan now is to open the c-file by taking on d4 and then put a rook on c8.} *

