1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ {[%cal Rb5e8] The Moscow Variation is practically as 
equally popular as the main lines of the open Sicilian. It conveniently allows 
White to avoid the forcing lines of the open Sicilians while at the same time 
giving him a playable middlegame position.} Bd7 {[%cal Rd7b5] Of the three 
possible moves this one is the simplest. After the exchange of the bishops 
Black's position will be easier to play as the exchanges favour the side with 
less space.} 4. Bxd7+ {The main move. The alternatives are less ambitious.} Nxd7 
{[%cal Be7e6,Bg8f6,Bf8e7,Be8g8,Ba8c8] With this recapture Black aims for quick 
development after ...Ngf6, ...e6, ...Be7 and ...O-O.} 5. O-O {[%cal 
Bc2c3,Bd2d4,Bf1e1,Gc3d4]} Ngf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] Attacking the e4-pawn and asking 
White to determine his intentions. Speaking of White's plans, he has two main 
ones at his disposal: 1. To go for the hedgehog formation with c4 and d4, or 2. 
To play for a full centre with c3 and d4. Both these plans can be executed with 
a queen on e2 or a rook on e1, which means we have 4 possible set-ups for 
White.} 6. Re1 {[%cal Bc2c3,Bd2d4,Gc3d4] Here we will explore both plans (the 
hedgehog and going for c3 and d4) with a rook on e1.} e6 {[%cal Bf8e7,Be8g8]} 7. 
c3 {[%cal Gc3d4,Bd2d4] White wants to establish a full centre by pushing d4.} 
Be7 {Black continues his normal development.} 8. d4 O-O {[%cal 
Bc5d4,Bd6d5,Ba8c8] In these positions when White has the full centre Black can 
simply ignore it because he has smooth development and any pawn advance can 
easily be absorbed.} 9. e5 {[%cal Ge4d5][%csl Rd5] This push puts immediate 
pressure, but the line shows how Black absorbs this pressure.} Ne8 {[%cal 
Be8c7,Bc7d5] The knight retreats, but it can easily arrive on d5 via c7.} 10. 
exd6 {This resolves the tension in the centre.} Bxd6 {[%cal Be8f6] Both 
recaptures are possible, but with the e5-pawn gone the knight from e8 can return 
to f6.} 11. Na3 {[%cal Ba3c4,Gc4d6] White also needs to develop.} cxd4 {[%cal 
Bd6c5] This capture wins the c5-square for the bishop in case it is attacked by} 
12. Nc4 Bc5 13. Nxd4 Nef6 {[%cal Ba7a6,Bb7b5][%csl Gc5,Gd7,Gf6] Black has an 
excellent position. He has no weaknesses and has smooth play with his pieces.} *

