1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ {[%cal Rb5e8] The Moscow Variation is practically as 
equally popular as the main lines of the open Sicilian.} Bd7 {[%cal Rd7b5] Of 
the three possible moves this one is the simplest. After the exchange of the 
bishops Black's position will be easier to play as the exchanges favour the side 
with less space.} 4. Bxd7+ {The main move. The alternatives are less ambitious.} 
Nxd7 {[%cal Be7e6,Bg8f6,Bf8e7,Be8g8,Ba8c8] With this recapture Black aims for 
quick development after ...Ngf6, ...e6, ...Be7 and ...O-O.} 5. O-O {[%cal 
Bd1e2,Bc2c4,Bd2d4]} Ngf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] Attacking the e4-pawn and asking White to 
determine his intentions. Speaking of White's plans, he has two main ones at his 
disposal: 1. To go for the Maroczy formation with c4 and d4, or 2. To play for a 
full centre with c3 and d4. Both these plans can be executed with a queen on e2 
or a rook on e1, which means we have 4 possible set-ups for White.} 6. Qe2 
{[%cal Bc2c4,Bd2d4] The Maroczy plan with a queen on e2 is considered the most 
promising for White.} e6 7. b3 {[%cal Bc1b2,Bc2c4,Gb3c4] This is considered the 
most precise way to prepare for the hedgehog formation that Black is aiming for. 
The point is to have the c4-pawn already protected once it lands there.} Be7 
{[%cal Ba8c8,Be8g8]} 8. Bb2 O-O 9. c4 Rc8 10. Nc3 {[%cal 
Gc3e4,Bd2d4,Rd6d5,Rd5e4] This is more precise as the immediate 10. d4 can be met 
by 10... d5!} Re8 $1 {[%cal Rc5d4,Ge8e2,Be7f8][%csl Re2] An important move! 
While it follows the already-mentioned rule of thumb for the hedgehog to put the 
rook on the same file as the queen, it also allows Black to postpone the capture 
on d4.} 11. d4 Bf8 {Another important move. Thanks to the rook on e8 Black can 
postpone the capture on d4.} 12. Rad1 Qa5 {[%cal Rd4d5,Re8e2][%csl Re2] Black 
plays all the useful moves before taking on d4.} 13. Qd2 cxd4 {Now finally Black 
takes on d4.} 14. Nxd4 a6 {[%cal Ga6b5,Rc3b5,Rd4b5] Eventually we ended up in a 
typical hedgehog position, but White was forced to lose a tempo by moving the 
queen. Black is comfortably placed and ready for the middlegame.} *

