1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 {[%cal Bc2c4,Bb1c3,Bc1g5,Be1c1][%csl Rd4] 
With this recapture White has two ideas, depending on Black's response - either 
to obtain a Maroczy bind by playing c4, or to obtain quick development by Nc3, 
Bg5 and O-O-O, aiming for a kingside attack.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4]} 5. Bb5 {[%cal 
Rb5e8] This move is considered the main one, but the alternative is also decent 
and has gained some traction recently.} a6 {[%cal Ga6b5] Again the most direct 
move. Black forces the exchange on c6, thus gaining the bishop pair and 
strengthening the centre.} 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 {[%cal Gb8b1][%csl Gc8]} 7. O-O {[%cal 
Bc2c4]} e5 {[%csl Ge5,Gd6,Gc6] With the compact pawn mass in the centre Black 
will comfortably develop behind it.} 8. Qd3 Qc7 {[%cal Rc1g5,Rg5d8,Rg8f6][%csl 
Gc7] It is more precise to start with the queen move in order to avoid the pin 
after 9. Bg5.} 9. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4]} Nf6 10. Nc3 Be7 {[%cal Be8g8]} 11. b3 
{[%cal Bc1b2,Bc1a3] This move allows for possible development of the bishop to 
b2 or a3.} O-O 12. h3 {[%cal Gh3g4,Rc8g4] Since the development of the bishop on 
g4 is what Black would like to obtain, White is preventing it.} h6 {[%cal 
Gh6g5,Rf3g5,Rg5e6,Bc8e6] Black also opens a luft for the king and prepares the 
development of the bishop on e6, thus not fearing Ng5.} 13. Rd1 {[%cal 
Gd1d6][%csl Rd6]} Be6 {[%cal Bf6d7,Bf6h5,Bf7f5] Black is fully developed and is 
now ready for the middlegame. His main active idea is the ...f5 push and he can 
achieve this by either ...Nd7 or ...Nh5.} *

