1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. f3 {[%cal Bc2c4,Rb1c3] The idea of 
this move is to allow for the move c4 before putting the knight on c3, thus 
establishing a Maroczy bind.} e5 {[%cal Bd6d5,Ge5d4] The typical Najdorf move 
here is a preparation for ...d5.} 6. Nb3 {Lately White's attempts were connected 
with this move.} d5 {[%cal Gd5c4] Immediately liberating the position and not 
allowing c4.} 7. Bg5 {[%cal Rg5d8,Be4d5]} Be6 {[%cal Ge6d5] Defending the 
centre.} 8. Bxf6 gxf6 9. exd5 Qxd5 {[%csl Ge6,Gf8] With the pair of bishops 
Black is fine in the endgame.} 10. Qxd5 Bxd5 11. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5]} Be6 {[%csl 
Ge6,Gf8,Rf7,Rf6,Re5] Black has the pair of bishops while White has the better 
structure and a slight lead in development. With some precise play Black can 
neutralise White's trumps.} *

